  "assistantText": "Perfect! ✅ Circuit built successfully. Here's your counter with button-triggered increment:\n\n---\n\n## **Wiring Table**\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component       | Pin Role  | Description                    |\n|-------------|-----------------|-----------|--------------------------------|\n| **D2**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment A | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D3**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment B | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D4**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment C | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D5**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment D | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D6**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment E | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D7**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment F | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D8**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment G | Via 220Ω resistor              |\n| **D12**     | Button          | Signal    | Pulled HIGH internally         |\n| **GND**     | 7-Segment GND   | —         | Common cathode return          |\n| **GND**     | Button GND      | —         | Button return to ground        |\n\n---\n\n## **How It Works**\n\n1. **Button Press Detection**: When you press the button (D12 goes LOW), debouncing logic waits 50ms to ignore bounces.\n2. **Counter Increment**: Counter increases by 1 on button release.\n3. **Wraparound**: After reaching 9, the counter resets to 0.\n4. **Display Update**: The `displayDigit()` function sets the 7 segments to show digits 0–9 using if/else logic.\n5. **Segment Mapping**: Each segment pin (D2–D8) drives its segment through a 220Ω current-limiting resistor.\n\n---\n\n## **Power Budget**\n\n| Item | Current |\n|------|---------|\n| **Per Segment** (7×220Ω @ 5V) | ~20mA each @ max brightness |\n| **Max active segments per digit** | 7 segments (digit 8) |\n| **Display + Resistors** | ~140mA (peak, all 7 segments lit) |\n| **Button circuit** | <1mA (internal pullup) |\n| **Arduino D2–D8 pins** | ~20mA each (safe within spec) |\n| **Total Board Draw** | ~141mA (well within Arduino Uno 500mA limit) |\n\n**✓ Safe**: All pins individually ≤20mA, total draw comfortably under board limits.\n\n---\n\n## **Arduino Sketch Code** (Complete)\n\n```cpp\nint counter = 0;\nint buttonPin = 12;\nint lastButtonState = HIGH;\nunsigned long lastDebounceTime = 0;\nunsigned long debounceDelay = 50;\n\n// Segment pins: a, b, c, d, e, f, g\nint segmentPins[7] = {2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8};\n\nvoid setup() {\n  pinMode(buttonPin, INPUT_PULLUP);\n  for (int i = 0; i < 7; i++) {\n    pinMode(segmentPins[i], OUTPUT);\n  }\n  displayDigit(0);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  int buttonState = digitalRead(buttonPin);\n  \n  if (buttonState != lastButtonState) {\n    lastDebounceTime = millis();\n  }\n  \n  if ((millis() - lastDebounceTime) > debounceDelay) {\n    if (buttonState == LOW && lastButtonState == HIGH) {\n      counter++;\n      if (counter > 9) {\n        counter = 0;\n      }\n      displayDigit(counter);\n    }\n  }\n  \n  lastButtonState = buttonState;\n}\n\nvoid displayDigit(int digit) {\n  if (digit == 0) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0);\n  } else if (digit == 1) {\n    setSegments(0, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0);\n  } else if (digit == 2) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 3) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 4) {\n    setSegments(0, 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 5) {\n    setSegments(1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 6) {\n    setSegments(1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 7) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0);\n  } else if (digit == 8) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1);\n  } else if (digit == 9) {\n    setSegments(1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1);\n  }\n}\n\nvoid setSegments(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g) {\n  digitalWrite(2, a);\n  digitalWrite(3, b);\n  digitalWrite(4, c);\n  digitalWrite(5, d);\n  digitalWrite(6, e);\n  digitalWrite(7, f);\n  digitalWrite(8, g);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\nYour counter is ready! Press the button